While Wisconsin is seen as one of the blue wall states, The Republican party there is hyper competitive and tends to win the off year elections. The Republicans have a long history of winning key state elections, and with the seventh party system forming the Republicans are only gaining appeal in that state.

sobering primary results in the Senate race:
No change. Ron Johnson continues to be a bad politician. All Dem candidates have consolidated around one candidate.
Roe/Kansas changes things... Maybe..

On the Democratic side of the race, Lasry who was largely self-funding his campaign with $12m of his own $ and making life difficult for Barnes has dropped out of the race, endorsing Barnes. Earlier in the week another strong D challenger to Barnes suspended his campaign and also endorsed Barnes. This makes Barnes the likely D candidate and enables him to start shifting his attention to defeating Ron Johnson.
johnson doesn't look as strong as he did several months ago, but he is still rich.
Only because Ron Johnson luck can hold only so long. The state is starting to turn purple again

I think Sen. Johnson has gone completely extreme. I also understand he does not spend much time at home. I think there is a enough progressive energy in WI to boot Sen. Johnson from his seat. I think there are stronger Democratic candidates than Republican candidates in WI. I think Sen. Johnson's current extreme views are too extreme in a post-roe country.

I am treating the 538 forecast as a base rate, and Silver gives the Republicans a 72% chance. I make a slight downward adjustment because I see a slight upward trend in the odds for Dems - who gained 5 points in the last 30 days or so.

In the wake of Roe being overturned, these odds are moving a bit more toward the Democrats. For the Democrats to actually win a state like Wisconsin, you would especially want to see Biden's approval ratings go back up.

Democrats lack a strong candidate running for their primary, and this will likely be a red wave year with a deeply unpopular President. Unless something drastically changes, I just can't see any scenarios in which Ron Johnson loses.
